  <body>
    <sec>
      <title>Introduction</title>
      <p>Widgets have become an essential component in modern engineering
      systems. Their performance characteristics directly impact the overall
      system reliability and efficiency.</p>
      <p>Previous studies <xref ref-type="bibr" rid="ref1">Smith 2020</xref>
      have examined widget behavior under controlled conditions, but
      real-world performance remains poorly understood.</p>
    </sec>
    <sec>
      <title>Materials and Methods</title>
      <p>We selected 200 widgets from three manufacturers for testing.</p>
      <sec>
        <title>Widget Categories</title>
        <list list-type="bullet">
          <list-item><p>Type A: Standard aluminum widgets</p></list-item>
          <list-item><p>Type B: Reinforced steel widgets</p></list-item>
          <list-item><p>Type C: Composite polymer widgets</p></list-item>
        </list>
      </sec>
      <sec>
        <title>Test Protocol</title>
        <list list-type="order">
          <list-item><p>Initial calibration</p></list-item>
          <list-item><p>Stress testing at 50%, 75%, and 100% load</p></list-item>
          <list-item><p>Environmental cycling</p></list-item>
        </list>
      </sec>
    </sec>
    <sec>
